    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory using pandas. For each file, return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count, 2) distinct cmdb_id values (list), 3) earliest and latest timestamp values (as integer seconds), and 4) top up to 20 unique KPI/trace/log names with their occurrence counts (for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name, for error_logs.csv show top 20 messages by frequency). Keep outputs small and structured (one summary per file). Do not filter by incident window yet." }

{
    "analysis": "From the telemetry load summary: metric, trace, and log CSVs are populated across many services and cover the incident time range; error_logs.csv is empty. Common metric KPI names include cpu, mem, socket, diskio, workload, latency-50, latency-90, and error. Trace features include many from/to entries involving ts-* services. Log.csv contains log.error_count and log.row_count. To follow the required workflow, next we should preprocess metric series for the candidate root-cause services only (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service): compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) per component-KPI using the full available metric series, then filter metrics to the incident window (2024-01-25 00:51:17 to 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC) and detect anomalies (points > P95 or < P5). This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs for further trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv into pandas. Keep full series in memory. Restrict rows to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global statistics over the full file: count, global_p95, global_p5, global_mean. Then parse timestamp to UTC datetimes and filter rows to the incident window from 2024-01-25 00:51:17 UTC to 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that has data in the incident window, return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window (int), latest_ts_in_window (int), count_above_p95_in_window, max_value_in_window, count_below_p5_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Limit output to rows with count_in_window>0, sorted by count_above_p95_in_window descending then count_in_window descending, and return at most 50 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous step (metrics analysis) computed global thresholds per (service, KPI) for the five candidate services and filtered metric points to the incident window. Result: 36 (service,KPI) series had data in-window. Many series show only 1–2 samples above their global P95 (short, isolated spikes). No KPI shows sustained or widespread P95 exceedance during the incident window. Since multiple services show small spikes, we must use traces to determine which (if any) service is the downstream faulty component in the call chain, and use logs for confirmation of the failure reason. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next atomic step is trace analysis: compute global thresholds for trace time series (using full trace.csv), then inspect trace data within the incident window to find trace-level anomalies (e.g., elevated duration or error_rate) and the earliest anomaly timestamps to identify downstream faulty services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv into pandas. For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global_p95 and global_p5 using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calculation). Then parse timestamps to UTC datetimes and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:51:17 UTC through 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) that has data in the incident window, compute: count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window (int), latest_ts_in_window (int), count_above_global_p95_in_window, max_value_in_window, count_below_global_p5_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95. Return a compact table of rows where count_above_global_p95_in_window>0, sorted by count_above_global_p95_in_window descending then earliest_ts_in_window ascending, limited to top 20 rows. Include only the columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window, latest_ts_in_window, count_above_global_p95_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95. If there are no rows with count_above_global_p95_in_window>0, instead return the top 20 trace series by count_in_window with the same columns." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found brief, simultaneous latency spikes (2 samples out of 25) from the root to many downstream services (including ts-auth-service and ts-order-service). Metric analysis across the five candidate services showed only very short, low-count spikes (1–2 samples) across many KPIs (cpu, mem, diskio, socket, latency), with no sustained exceedances or any non-zero error KPI for ts-travel-service. error_logs.csv is empty. Together this pattern points to brief, system-wide latency blips affecting multiple downstream calls rather than a sustained resource exhaustion or persistent service crash. To distinguish between transient network latency/packet loss versus short CPU/disk blips on a specific service, we need to inspect normalized log features (log.error_count, log.row_count) for the candidate services during the incident window to see if there are drops in row_count or spikes in error_count that align with the trace spikes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv into pandas. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global_p95 and global_p5 using the full file (do NOT pre-filter by time). Then convert timestamps to UTC datetimes and filter to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:51:17 UTC through 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, log_name) that has data in-window, compute: count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window (int), latest_ts_in_window (int), count_above_global_p95_in_window, max_value_in_window, count_below_global_p5_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Return rows where count_above_global_p95_in_window>0 OR count_below_global_p5_in_window>0, sorted by count_above_global_p95_in_window descending then count_below_global_p5_in_window descending, limited to top 20 rows. Include only columns: cmdb_id, log_name, count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window, latest_ts_in_window, count_above_global_p95_in_window, max_value_in_window, count_below_global_p5_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace and log summaries show brief, simultaneous anomalies across many services during the incident window: traces from root to many downstream services (including ts-auth-service and ts-order-service) had 2 samples > global P95, and log.row_count for ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, and ts-travel-service also had short spikes and drops. Metrics for the five candidate services show isolated 1–2-sample spikes across multiple KPIs but no sustained resource exhaustion. To localize the root cause we must identify which candidate service is the downstream faulty service in the call chains and the earliest time its trace anomalies occur. The next step is therefore focused trace-level correlation targeting the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service): find trace series that target these services (trace.to_ts-<service>.* or trace.from_ts-<service>.*), count anomalies > global P95 within the incident window, and extract the earliest anomaly timestamp per series. This will let us see which candidate service shows trace-level degradation first (and thus is likely the downstream faulty service).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Compute global_p95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace series. Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:51:17 UTC through 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC. From the filtered traces, select only trace_name entries that reference any of the candidate services: 'ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service' (match both 'to_ts-<service>' and 'from_ts-<service>' occurrences). For each matching (trace_name) compute: count_in_window, count_above_global_p95_in_window, earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window (the smallest timestamp in-window where value>global_p95; null if none), max_value_in_window, global_p95. Return rows with count_above_global_p95_in_window>0 sorted by earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window ascending, limited to 20 rows. Include columns: trace_name, count_in_window, count_above_global_p95_in_window, earliest_anomaly_ts_in_window (int), max_value_in_window, global_p95." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps computed global thresholds and inspected metrics, traces, and logs. Metrics across the five candidate services show only short, low-count spikes (1–2 samples) across many KPIs. Trace analysis showed brief latency spikes from the root to many downstream services (2/25 samples each) but when specifically filtering traces that reference the candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) there were no trace series with samples above their global P95 in the incident window. Log analysis shows that several services (notably ts-route-service and ts-travel-service, and also ts-order-service and ts-auth-service) had short-lived deviations in log.row_count during the window — including samples well below their historical P5 (indicating transient drops in traffic) and samples above P95 (spikes). error_logs.csv is empty. Together: (1) trace-wide short latency blips from root to many services, (2) widespread 1–2-sample metric spikes, and (3) several services exhibiting both upward and downward row_count anomalies — this pattern suggests a transient network-level issue (latency or packet loss) impacting many downstream calls rather than a single service resource exhaustion. However, the candidate service list requires we pick a service-level root cause. Among candidates, ts-route-service shows pronounced row_count drops (min much lower than global P5) and notable deviations, making it the strongest service-level candidate for causing observed client-perceived failures (dropped requests or delayed responses). To confirm, we should extract per-KPI anomaly timings for ts-route-service (metrics and logs) within the incident window to see earliest anomaly timestamps and severity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and log.csv. Compute global_p95 and global_p5 per (cmdb_id='ts-route-service', kpi_name) using the full metric.csv and per (cmdb_id='ts-route-service', log_name) using the full log.csv (do NOT filter before computing thresholds). Then filter both datasets to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:51:17 UTC through 2024-01-25 01:21:17 UTC (inclusive). For each metric/kpi and for each log_name belonging to ts-route-service that has data in-window, return a compact row with: component='ts-route-service', series_name (kpi_name or log_name), count_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window (int), latest_ts_in_window (int), count_above_global_p95_in_window, earliest_ts_above_global_p95_in_window (int or null), max_value_in_window, count_below_global_p5_in_window, earliest_ts_below_global_p5_in_window (int or null), min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Only return rows where count_above_global_p95_in_window>0 OR count_below_global_p5_in_window>0. Sort by earliest_ts_below_global_p5_in_window ascending (nulls last) then earliest_ts_above_global_p95_in_window ascending. Limit output to top 20 rows." }

